commentText: As a technical writer who's performed in both the User Manual Writer and the Documentation Writer spaces for 35 years or so, a few words of advice:  *_1  If you're going to be hired for your writing skills, you'd better have some._*  I've known a lot of 'technical writers' that struggled to deliver a product at a 6th grade level, while most corporate or government technical writing is going to be at 12th grade level or up.  *_2  Don't expect AI to save you._*  Technical writing is typically very narrow in scope and since the content will likely be new, any LLM-trained AI is not going to be able to write your content for you.  *_3  In addition to crafting prose in the King's English, you'll also need familiarity with HTML, SGML, and XML._*  Familiarity with different graphics formats, and their advantages/disadvantages, is a MUST.  *_4  Lastly, as a technical writer, you're going to need technical background beyond being able to record a macro in Microsoft Word._*  I spent 22 years as a Navy Electronics Tech with over 8000 hours of technical training.  That was a good start.

commentText: Actuarial analyst:  strong mathematical ability doesn't even come close to the level of math needed.  Imagine you have 1,000 people in a room who say they have a very strong mathematical skill set.  Maybe 3 of them have enough to be an actuary.  I have a B.S. in electrical engineering emphasizing CPU design.  Never got into the field because I graduated during the high tech bubble burst (no jobs at any company, anywhere in the world).  I do data analysis in the insurance industry.  Decided to self-study for the actuary exams.  My degree had calc 1-2-3, diff EQ, linear algebra, probability & stats (a very tough version specifically for EE majors), and linear programming & optimization.  Most of my core EE major classes were taught using all that math, so it is like I had those classes over and over again.  I retained all that knowledge even to this day.  I can literally walk into a final exam without cracking a book and do well.  I'm no idiot.  After studying for 1-year on my own, I got a 0 out of 10 on the 1st actuary test, Exam P.

commentText: Thanks for covering this topic. Myself and many classmates are Engineering graduates from top Canadian university. We all got 2 years of co-op work experience and decent projects...but 4 months of job hunting and still no luck!  Even if we decide to go for Masters, we will come out and expected to have minimum 5+years of experience for entry level positions.  How is this sustainable? Specially in a country with rising living expenses YoY.  In reality it just makes our degree less worth it.. a $100k investment.

Most of the times, your commute, health, gyms, movies, concerts, food allowances are taken care by the company so you don‚Äôt end up paying much on this. Moreover, in India we have the concept of CTC which largely inflated figure while in Europe your get base pay as your salary. So if your earn 7000‚Ç¨ per month, you will get almost 4500-5000‚Ç¨ in hand and after all the expenses while still enjoying the best life standards, clean environment you can easily save 3000-3500 ‚Ç¨ per month even if you compare the purchasing power. At the end, you enjoy the best working culture, fantastic work life balance and handsome salary. Of course it depends on people to people and their earnings / spending habits. If you save 3L per month, that ends up to 36L of pure savings. Even a 80LPA cannot save 36 L while meeting the standards of EU. So it‚Äôs not comparable. commentText: There is no such thing as a dream job unless you are self employed in your home town with good income, surrounded by your grannies and nannies and eating home food every day sitting on the lap of your mother! Every job is a challenge and a compromise and the further you get out from your comfort home or country the more challenging it gets. That is where Indian youths who have been pampered at home fail abroad with social adjustment in a new society. They are home sick all the time. They should be concentrating on learning new language, new culture, new skills, seeing new places, experiencing the diversity and nature and even enjoying the quietness and lonliness filled with personal advancement. Glad that you pointed out many of these things here. Europe or any where else is definitely not a bed of roses. Nobody is waiting for you with open arms to give you a job, a home or a car. It is a healthy struggle here all the way minus nepotism, corruption, unequality and injustice which you are hopefully trying to get away from.
